<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Unknown' Members of Cabinet Profiled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Unknown' Members of Cabinet Profiled </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105142594 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1100 
GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There were a few surprises and many confirmations in 
the new cabinet. Let us quickly run through the new members of 
Silvio Berlusconi's government. Mauro Lozzi reports: 
  [Lozzi] Among the 25 ministers sworn in this morning before 
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, there are six faces which are 
completely unknown to the public at large. 
  The new foreign trade minister is a technocrat and his name 
is Giorgio Bernini. Bernini, 66, is a commercial law professor 
at the University of Bologna. An expert in arbitration, he 
gained his seat in the Umbria region running on the Forza Italia 
ticket. 
  The man in charge of the Universities and Research Ministry 
is also from Forza Italia. His name is Stefano Podesta and he 
is 45. He is a professor at Bocconi University in Milan, where 
he teaches commercial economics. Until 30 April, he sat on the 
board of the Rizzoli Publishing Company. 
  Altero Matteoli will be in charge at the Environment 
Ministry. He is 53 and was a company director until he took 
charge of the Italian Social Movement's organizational sector. 
He has been a parliamentarian for a long time. 
  For the first time there is a woman in charge at the 
Agriculture Ministry. Her name is Adriana Poli-Bortone and she 
is an associated professor of Latin literature at the University 
of Lecce. She had already been elected on an Italian Social 
Movement ticket, and in past legislation has espoused the causes 
of pension rights, the education system, and women's issues. 
  Roberto Radice was elected on a Forza Italia ticket and will 
be in charge of the Public Works Ministry. He is a businessman 
and a member of the executive board of the National 
Confederation of Small Manufacturers [Confapi]. He is new to 
parliament. 
  Finally we have Antonio Guidi. He is 49, and a surgeon. 
Guidi will leave a trade union background to take charge of the 
Family Ministry. Guidi himself is handicapped, and while he was 
at the Italian General Confederation of Labor he was 
particularly concerned with the issue of employment for the 
disabled. 

</TEXT>

