<F P=101> Norway </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Investigate Italian Fascist Ministers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Investigate Italian Fascist Ministers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105135994 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1300 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ulla-Marie Johansen in Oslo] </F>
  [Text] The Norwegian Government wants to investigate the 
background of the fascist members of the newly appointed Italian 
Government before meetings are held between the two countries' 
ministers. Norwegian Foreign Minister Bjorn Tore Godal says 
cooperation will not be successful if direct links to 
Mussolini's supporter organizations are discovered in the past 
of the four ministers concerned. 
  [Johansen] Socialist Left Party Chairman Erik Solheim 
stressed in parliament today that fascism in Europe is not a 
common phenomenon but a criminal ideology and he wanted to know 
what attitude the government intends to take toward the four 
fascist ministers in the new Italian Government. Solheim asked 
whether the government intends to meet with the Italian 
ministers of culture, environmental protection, agriculture, and 
transport at ministerial level. 
  Foreign Minister Bjorn Tore Godal announced that the 
Norwegian Government intends to assess the ministers concerned 
on the basis of the replies they have given. If they are 
fascists without any direct line to Mussolini, then they pose no 
problem. Should one of them belong to this gang, links will be 
out of the question, Norwegian Foreign Minister Bjorn Tore Godal 
stated sharply in a reply given in parliament today. 

</TEXT>

