<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., UN, Turkish Officials Meet in Vienna </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., UN, Turkish Officials Meet in Vienna </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1105210994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1900 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1105210994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Robert Lamb, the U.S. State Department special 
coordinator on the Cyprus issue; Gustave Feissel, the UN 
secretary general's alternate special representative in Cyprus; 
and Turkish Deputy Foreign Minister Tugay Ulucevic today met in 
Vienna to discuss the situation after the deadlock in the talks 
on the confidence-building measures. The latest effort is 
taking place just a few days before the UN secretary general 
submits his report to the Security Council. 
  The negotiations will continue tomorrow. Two representatives 
of Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas are also participating in 
the meeting. It is felt that there is no chance for the talks 
to succeed because the Turkish side insists on maintaining its 
intransigent position. The Security Council is committed to 
studying alternate ways of promoting the Cyprus issue if it is 
ascertained that the UN secretary general's current effort has 
failed. 
  The Cypriot Government has said it does not expect anything 
from this meeting, because it does not believe that Turkish 
intransigence will bend. In Athens, the Greek Foreign Ministry 
spokesman said the meeting shows that the international 
community recognizes the need for making efforts toward the 
Turkish side. The spokesman stressed that the Greek Government 
hopes the UN secretary general's report will condemn Turkish 
intransigence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

