<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments on UN Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Comments on UN Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1105212894 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1900 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1105212894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Returning tonight from his visit to Barbados, 
Canada, and Strasbourg, Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis 
said the Greek Cypriot side expects the UN secretary general to 
circulate his report on the Cyprus issue, which will tell the 
truth about what has happened and the positions of the two sides 
in the upcoming talks on the confidence-building measures. 
  Mikhailidhis said any further delay in the circulation of 
the 
report endangers the credibility of the procedure. He noted 
that our side has no objection if others want to continue 
persuading the Turkish side to accept the UN document of 21 
March. The foreign minister added: Our side, however, objects 
to interventions in the circulation of the report and actions 
that will question the image and the credibility of the 
procedure. The confidence-building measures issue acted as a 
catalyst to show foreigners that Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot 
side have no political will for any solution. 
  Mikhailidhis stressed that Cyprus' closeness to Europe will 
continue despite threats by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas, 
who is obviously concerned that Cyprus' course toward Europe 
will proceed. 
  The foreign minister said that by abandoning the 
confidence-building measures to discuss the substance of the 
Cyprus issue, we are essentially opening the door for Denktas to 
escape from the difficult position he is in. He added that if 
the UN secretary general's efforts fail, we will ask the 
Security Council to adopt alternative ways to implement the 
resolutions on Cyprus. 

</TEXT>

