<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundestag Group Interrupts Visit to Northern Iraq </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bundestag Group Interrupts Visit to Northern Iraq </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905122294 Hamburg DPA in German 0936 GMT 9 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0905122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- According to Social Democratic Party Deputy 
Volker Neumann, three Bundestag deputies have interrupted an 
inspection visit to the autonomous Kurdish regions in northern 
Iraq because of heavy fighting between hostile Kurdish groups. 
Neumann reported in Bonn on Monday [9 April] that several 
hundred people have already been killed in the war between 
Mas'ud Barzani's Democratic Party of Kurdistan (DPK) and Jalal 
Talabani's Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK). The two party 
leaders cooperate in a coalition government of the autonomous 
region, while their supporters attacked one another on their way 
to negotiations. 
  The German delegation was led by the chairman of the 
Bundestag Subcommittee for Humanitarian Issues, Friedrich Vogel 
(Christian Democratic Union -- CDU). Heinrich Lummer (CDU) was 
the third participant. Neumann reported that members of aid 
organizations, including Eberhard Walde of the German liaison 
office in the region, have left the region, because their 
security can no longer be guaranteed. Representatives of the 
two warring parties called this "the saddest day" since Saddam 
Husayn's anti-Kurdish massacrers. 
  The deputies wanted to obtain some information on the extent 
of reconstruction aid provided for the autonomous region in 
Iraq, to which the Federal Government, and especially the 
laender of Lower Saxony and North Rhine-Westphalia have 
contributed. Germany's food aid could, however, be largely 
discontinued due to good harvests in 1992 and 1993, Neumann 
said. In these two years, Bonn provided almost 40 million marks 
in humanitarian aid. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

