<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Money Supply Reported Up 4.9 Percent in March </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Money Supply Reported Up 4.9 Percent in March </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1005110394 Hamburg DPA in German 0846 GMT 10 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1005110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt/Main -- In March, the money supply, M-3, 
increased by 4.9 percent over the fourth quarter of 1993. This 
leads to an extrapolated annual rate of 15.4 percent. With this 
final figure, the Bundesbank on Tuesday [10 May] slightly 
modified the figures it had originally predicted. The original 
annual rate indicated for March had been 15.2 percent. 
  The M-3 money supply contains the circulation of notes and 
coins, cash deposits, time deposits under four years, as well as 
savings deposits. There was an extremely large increase in the 
stock of money due to special factors at the beginning of this 
year. This "basic effect" influences monthly figures. For 
1994, the Bundesbank is aiming at a money supply growth rate of 
4 to 6 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

