<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU To Halt Market Barriers to Russian Products </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU To Halt Market Barriers to Russian Products </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205161994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1504 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN)--The European Union (EU) intends to 
abolish most of the market barriers to Russian products as of 
1995. This was announced by Federal Economics Minister Guenther 
Rexrodt in a conversation with BERLINER ZEITUNG (Friday [13 May] 
edition). Rexrodt, who conducted negotiations with Russian 
counterpart Aleksandr Shokhin on the sidelines of the Yeltsin 
visit to Bonn, said that, with the exception of "a number of 
steel and textile products and the agricultural area," there 
will be "totally open markets." He, therefore, considers 
Moscow's complaints of blocked access to the markets as "not 
quite justified." 
  The economics minister called the agreement achieved on 
future deliveries of railway cars by Deutsche Waggonbau AG 
Ammendorf to Russia a "breakthrough." The impending catastrophe 
for the company in Halle has been averted. Rexrodt confirmed 
during the conversation that Moscow had offered MiG-29's to pay 
the debts owed to Germany. However, "we have rejected that. It 
does not fit with our military and research plans. At present, 
we are unable to agree to such a deal," the minister said. 

</TEXT>

