<H3> <TI>   Announces `Imminent' Release of Detainees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Announces `Imminent' Release of Detainees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205171694 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The 11 French people of Premiere Urgence who have 
been detained by the Bosnian Serbs for more than a month now 
could be released within the next few hours. Their imminent 
release was announced by the Serbs this morning and confirmed 
later by the European negotiator, Lord Owen. French Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe, who is in Washington, has confirmed this 
information to Philippe Reltien: 
  [Begin Juppe recording] I would like to take this 
opportunity 
to say a word about the 11 hostages. According to news that has 
reached me from Paris, and also from Belgrade or Sarajevo, a 
possible release of the hostages could take place within the 
next few hours. I am still very cautious on this matter because 
I have no confirmation. I would like to recall -- to deny 
certain reports circulated in France -- that since the 
hostage-taking in early April, not a single day has passed 
without our diplomats deploying their efforts in Belgrade, Pale, 
Sarajevo, at the United Nations, the Greek presidency, and our 
allies. We have ceaselessly applied pressure, explaining 
clearly to the Serbs that we will not accept a mockery of 
justice, that this was a hostage-taking, that there was 
manipulation, that we will not bargain, and that we want the 
release of all the hostages. If the news were to be 
confirmed--I repeat that I am cautious--this will be the result 
of this continuous and efficient diplomatic effort. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

