<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "South Africa-Italy: End to </F>
Sanctions Boosts Italian Exports"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 9 -- The dropping of trade 
sanctions against South Africa and the devaluation of the lira 
are behind the growth in Italy's business with the 
post-apartheid state, according to statistics for the first 11 
months of 1992-93 published by the Institute for the Promotion 
of Foreign Trade (ICE). 
  Imports show a modest increase of 4.7 percent, up from 2,887 
billion lire (1,804 million dollars) to 3,004 billion lire 
(1,877.5 million dollars), while exports to South Africa show a 
healthier growth trend of 35.7 percent, going from 679 billion 
lire (424.38 million dollars) to 921 billion lire (575.63 
million dollars). 
  Overall, there was an improvement of 30.6 percent in the 
Italian balance of trade with South Africa, with predictions for 
the coming year looking positive especially for Italian exports. 
  The following table compares Jan-Nov '93 exports to South 
Africa with the same period in '92. 


------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Products                 |Value (in billion lire)  |Percentage               | 
