<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Embassy Says Mafia Targets German Firms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Embassy Says Mafia Targets German Firms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1405165994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1115 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1405165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Siegburg/Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- German business 
representatives in Moscow seem to be increasingly at risk from 
the Russian mafia. This was the gist of an alarming telegram 
sent by the German Embassy in Moscow to the German Foreign 
Ministry headquarters, according to the `Bonn-Info' information 
service. Today a Foreign Ministry spokesman was unwilling either 
to deny or confirm the telegram for the moment because of the 
diplomatic nature of the message. 
  In the embassy's view, there is a "strong probability" of 
German associations and firms "coming into contact with 
organized crime sooner or later," particularly in Moscow and St. 
Petersburg. That only left a "choice between paying or 
leaving." The mafia was trying to plant "bookkeepers" to 
monitor company income to secure their "tax share" in the form 
of protection money. 
  Firms with retail outlets or storage buildings in particular 
were therefore coming to arrangements with blackmailers to 
prevent the risk of their buildings being "torched." The 
blackmailers were also frequently threatening the lives of the 
businessmen and their families. In its telegram, the embassy 
raises the question of whether the German Government should 
advise against business activity in Russia in the event of 
growing risks. Protection from the Russian authorities was 
"insufficiently guaranteed". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65278 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu094_h_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-094 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Savings Banks To Expand Cooperation With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Savings Banks To Expand Cooperation With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1605131394 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 13-14 May 94 
p 15 </F>

<F P=103> AU1605131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["vwd" report: "Cooperation With Russia"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn, 12 May -- Cooperation between German and 
Russian savings banks, which has existed since the end of 1991, 
is to be further developed and intensified. This has been 
agreed by Horst Koehler, president of the German Giro 
Association (DSGV), and Oleg Yashin, president of Rossberbank, 
at a meeting in Bonn. As the DSFV announced, the Russian 
savings bank, which has 42,000 offices, 200,000 employees, and a 
balance sheet sum of about 2 billion German marks, is among the 
five largest Russian banks and is the only Russian bank that has 
a nationwide network of offices. 
  According to the DSGV, other fields of cooperation are a 
small-loan program for the newly developing medium-sized 
industry in Nishniy-Novgorod, participation in financing housing 
construction and in leasing business, advice for the 
establishment of a savings bank association, as well as joint 
ventures with the Central German Handicrafts Association (ZDH), 
whose Secretary General Hanns-Eberhard Schleyer also attended 
the meeting in Bonn. Already, the German savings banks and land 
banks are participating in the establishment of a decentralized, 
market economy banking sector in Russia via the Savings Banks 
Foundation for International Cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

