<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Albania, Hungary, Slovenia Asked To Take Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Albania, Hungary, Slovenia Asked To Take Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1305131994 Paris AFP in English 1242 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1305131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Copenhagen, May 13 (AFP) -- Danish Interior and 
Immigration Minister Birte Weiss said Friday [13 May] she asked 
Albania, Hungary and Slovenia for authorisation to set up 
Danish-run camps for refugees from former Yugoslavia on their 
territories. 
  In a note to parliament, Weiss said there was no agreement 
so 
far to the requests, made in April, but that the government was 
continuing to seek an accord with the three countries. 
  Denmark runs a refugee camp in Bosnia-Herzegovina and 
another 
in Croatia but the Croatian authorities last month refused to 
allow Denmark to set up another one there. 
  Denmark has also offered shelter for some 18,000 refugees 
from ex-Yugoslavia but believes haven should be provided as 
close as possible to home to facilitate return and to cut 
government spending. 

</TEXT>

