<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rehn on Security Policy, EU Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rehn on Security Policy, EU Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1505191094 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1800 GMT 15 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1505191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to Defense Minister Elisabeth Rehn, 
membership in the European Union [EU] does not change Finland's 
security policy toward neighboring countries. Speaking in 
Vienna, Austria, Rehn gave assurances that cross-border 
countries will continue to hold an important position in 
bilateral relations irrespective of the EU. She addressed a 
meeting of the second government party, the People's Party. 
Defense Minister Rehn pointed out the end of the Cold War had 
not changed the situation in northern Europe. For Russia, the 
strategic importance of its northwestern corner had only grown 
following the breakup of the Soviet Union and nuclear 
disarmament. Rehn reiterated Finland's stance that a country 
could retain an independent defense and military nonalliance 
within the EU. 

</TEXT>

