<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papoulias Views Lifting U.S. Embargo in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papoulias Views Lifting U.S. Embargo in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1305131094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1305131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Serbian forces in Bosnia are escalating their 
attacks against the Muslim enclave of (Bihac) in western Bosnia 
while an interministerial conference is being held in Geneva 
aimed at ending the hostilities through political means. 
Participating in the conference are the foreign ministers of 
the United States, Russia, Britain, France, Germany, Greece, and 
Belgium as well as the international community mediators in the 
Bosnian issue. Their goal is to persuade the belligerent sides 
in Bosnia to return to the negotiating table. Greece is 
represented by Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias in his 
capacity as president of the European Union Foreign Ministers 
Council. 
  An ATHENS NEWS AGENCY dispatch from Geneva notes that the 
talks will open without any particular hopes and with the strong 
impression that there are substantive differences between the 
United States and France on charting a joint policy to impose a 
solution on the belligerent parties in Bosnia. The dispatch 
also stresses the difficulties that French Foreign Minister 
Alain Juppe had two days ago in persuading the U.S. leaders in 
Washington to exercise effective pressure on the Muslims in 
Bosnia. 
  It should be stressed that the U.S. Senate decided last 
night 
on the unilateral lifting of the arms embargo on the Muslims in 
Bosnia that was imposed by the United Nations. Shortly before 
leaving for Geneva, Foreign Minister Papoulias responded to 
questions from correspondents. Among other things, Papoulias 
said: The troika supports the EU action plan. U.S. Secretary 
of State Warren Christopher has his own ideas. Unfortunately, I 
have been informed that the U.S. Senate decided to lift the arms 
embargo on the Muslims in Bosnia. I think this decision could 
complicate the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65315 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu094_p_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-094 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Geneva Meeting Hailed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Geneva Meeting Hailed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1405210894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1904 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1405210894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Athens, May 14 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav President Zoran 
Lilic and Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou agreed on 
Saturday [14 May] that the ministerial meeting on Bosnia held in 
Geneva on Friday was major step in the direction of a political 
settlement of the crisis in former Yugoslavia. 
  The officials stressed as the most important that the whole 
negotiating process had been brought back to the framework of 
the European Union and its plan for Bosnia. 
  President Lilic is on a one-day visit to Athens en route 
from 
South Africa where he attended the ceremony of inauguration of 
President Nelson Mandela. 
  The foreign ministers of Russia, the United States, Great 
Britain, France and the European Union's "troika" (Belgium, 
Greece, Germany), meeting in Geneva on Friday, invited Bosnia's 
warring Moslems, Serbs and Croats to agree to a four-month 
ceasefire, "with provision of extension," in which to open talks 
on a settlement of their disputes under the guidance of the 
recently formed contact group. 
  The ministers coordinated a common strategy in the efforts 
for solving the Bosnian conflict, and approved the European 
Union's formula for Bosnia under which that war-wracked former 
Yugoslav republic should be divided in such a way as to give the 
Moslems and Croats 51 percent of the territory in which to form 
their federation, and the Serbs the remaining 49 percent. 
  Lilic and Papandreou stressed the need for an equal 
treatment 
of all sides to the conflict in order that a just final solution 
might be reached, and agreed on the necessity of abandoning the 
practice of pressure, ultimatums, intervention and imposition of 
patent solutions. 
  They hoped that the resumption of Geneva talks would be 
dominated by reason on all sides in order that a peace [word 
indistinct] might be signed and the crisis resolved. 
  The talk brought to light the view that the lifting of the 
UN 
Security Council's sanctions against Yugoslavia 
(Serbia/Montenegro), which were voted in place in May 1992 in 
retaliation for the country's alleged involvement in civil war 
in neighbouring Bosnia-Herzegovina, is a precondition for a 
peaceful settlement of the overall crisis in former Yugoslavia. 
  Lilic expressed his dissatisfaction that the Geneva 
ministerial meeting had not taken the position that the 
sanctions should be lifted, but added that the reference to 
their phased easing was nonetheless a positive step and an 
improvement on the earlier attitude and threats of intensifying 
pressure on Yugoslavia. 
  Lilic thanked Greece for its principled and firm position on 
the crisis in former Yugoslavia, particularly the problem of the 
sanctions. 
  He expressed fear that Turkish and U.S. military influences 
in the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM) and [word 
indistinct] might be a threat to the Balkan's and to Europe as a 
whole. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

