<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Answers Russian Note on Straits Traffic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Answers Russian Note on Straits Traffic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1305185994 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1305185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report] </F>
  [Text] The Russian Federation has submitted a note to the 
Turkish Embassy in Moscow on the statutes and regulations of the 
straits that will go into effect on 1 July, saying that they are 
not in line with the Montreux Treaty and that the traffic 
regulations of the straits should be solved at the international 
level. 
  The response that was conveyed to the Russian Foreign 
Ministry today states that it is Turkey's most natural right to 
regulate the maritime traffic in the straits in a way that will 
ensure maritime safety and protect the environment. According 
to information released by the Foreign Ministry, the note, whose 
contents were made public by the Russian Federation's foreign 
affairs spokesman, states that Russia shares Turkey's concern 
regarding the maritime safety of the straits but that this issue 
should be solved at the international level. 
  The Foreign Ministry announcement adds that the reply 
message 
conveyed to the Russian Federation expresses the following views: 
  We welcome the fact that the Russian Federation shares our 
concern regarding traffic safety in the Turkish straits and that 
it accepts the fact of the existence of an urgent and serious 
problem that needs to be solved. We, however, do not agree with 
the views that the statutes and regulations are in contravention 
of the Montreux Treaty and that they may be implemented 
arbitrarily. We believe that these views constitute a biased 
approach to technical regulations which we have not even begun 
to implement. The reply message further recalls that for the 
past 58 years, Turkey has been meticulously implementing the 
Montreux Treaty, adding that concerns regarding this issue are 
invalid. The message adds that the Turkish Government has no 
intention of unilaterally changing the Montreux Treaty and that 
the changes in the statute are nothing more than the reflection 
of international rules and regulations on domestic law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65323 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu094_q_94003" </HT>


