<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Labor MP Resigns From Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Labor MP Resigns From Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1705050394 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 0423 GMT 17 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1705050394 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Chris Moncrieff, political editor, PA News] </F>
  [Text] Bryan Gould, a former shadow cabinet minister, has 
officially resigned as an MP [Member of Parliament]. He is to 
return to his native New Zealand to take up an academic post. 
  This creates a by-election -- the sixth pending -- in 
Dagenham, in east London. He had already announced his 
intention to quit. 
  Mr. Gould, 55, a committed Euro-critic, fought John Smith 
for 
the leadership in 1992 as the torch-carrier of the left. But he 
was routed. 
  He resigned last night as an MP under the technicality of 
being appointed by the Chancellor as steward amd bailiff of the 
Manor of Northstead. This is an office of profit under the 
Crown and prevents its holder from serving as an MP. 
  The two offices of profit under the Crown which are 
alternatively used are the Chiltern Hundreds and the Manor of 
Northstead. Theoretically an MP cannot resign but can be 
disqualified by accepting such an office. 
  Holding them, however, generates no income, but a person's 
membership of the House automatically lapses. 
  General election result at Dagenham -- Bryan Gould (Labour) 
22,027; Don Rossiter (Conservative) 15,294; Charles Marquand 
(Liberal Democrat) 4,824. Majority 6,733. Turnout 70.7 
  The writ for the by-election may be moved today, along with 
others. It could take place on June 9, the same day as the 
European elections. 

</TEXT>

