<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Commission Predicts Economy To Improve </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Commission Predicts Economy To Improve </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1605095394 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 13-14 May 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU1605095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["wff" report: "Commission Is Spreading Optimism"] </F>
  [Text] Brussels, 12 May -- The Brussels Commission has 
worked out unusually positive forecasts for the economic 
development in the European Union (EU) for the discussions of 
the foreign, finance, and economics ministers who will meet in 
the Belgian capital next Monday [16 May]. For the first time in 
years, one is optimistic again, Danish EU Commission Vice 
President Henning Christophersen, who is responsible for 
economic policy, said. 
  A good upswing is just around the corner, Christophersen 
stated, pointing to his authority's forecasts, which are usually 
more pessimistic than those of other international 
organizations. Even if the predicted positive development does 
not continue, Brussels sees good prospects that a considerable 
number of member states will fulfill the most important 
criterion of the Maastricht Treaty for entering the final state 
of the Economic and Monetary Union in 1997- 98: current new 
state debts of no more than 3 percent of GNP. 
  The EU economic forecast now proceeds from an EU-wide real 
growth of 1.6 percent for this year and of 2.5 percent for 1995. 
The upswing is primarily supported by exports and by 
investments. Inflation continues to decline. Already in 1995 
-- and thus one year earlier than recommended -- it could be 2-3 
percent on average in the EU. Prospects on the labor market 
remain somber, however. According to Christophersen, the 
increase in the unemployment rate may come to a standstill 
during the first half of 1995, but it will remain at the high 
level of 11.75 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

