<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panel Proposes Eased Arms Export Procedures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panel Proposes Eased Arms Export Procedures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94EN0318F Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 21 Apr 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> 94EN0318F </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>
<F P=105>  Swedish </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Arms Export Permitted at a Lower </F>
Level?"] 
  [Text] The export of defense materiel will always need an 
export license even in the future, but it can be granted by the 
Ministry of Defense instead of by the government, which is now 
the primary licensing authority. This is the opinion of a 
working group at the Ministry of Defense that has studied the 
need for reforming the arms export legislation, particularly in 
view of the European Union. The group submitted its memorandum 
to Defense Minister Elisabeth Rehn on Wednesday [20 April]. 
  If required for reasons of foreign or security policy, the 
license could also in the future be issued by the government, 
says the working group. The working group included 
representatives of the Ministries of Defense, Foreign Affairs, 
Trade and Industry, as well as the Interior Ministry and the 
General Staff. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

