<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis, Others Discuss Results of Vienna Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kliridhis, Others Discuss Results of Vienna Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Government Prepares Action Plan </H4>

<F P=102> NC1605195894 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1900 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1605195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In an interview with the Cyprus Broadcasting 
Corporation, Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis said that 
after the Turkish side refused to cooperate on the 
confidence-building measures, the Cypriot Government began 
preparing an action plan to deal with the Cyprus issue. This 
plan is expected to be submitted after the UN secretary general 
submits his report to the Security Council. 
  Mikhailidhis said that expert legal advice was sought in the 
preparation of this report. He added that apart from the ideas 
that are already included in it, the action plan should be 
completed in a substantive manner and should include issues that 
will arise after Butrus-Ghali submits his report. 
  The foreign minister emphasized that the Greek Cypriot 
side's 
position stresses that the Security Council must examine ways to 
change the current unacceptable status quo and create 
prerequisites for a substantive dialogue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65375 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu095_o_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-095 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis, Others Discuss Results of Vienna Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kliridhis, Others Discuss Results of Vienna Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Turkey To Clarify Points </H4>

<F P=102> NC1605132794 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1605132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali will submit 
his report to the Security Council by the end of the week to 
give Turkey a chance to clarify some points raised in the Vienna 
talks last week. The Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation 
correspondent reported from New York that the extension given to 
the Turkish side expires tomorrow [17 May], when pseudo Prime 
Minister Haki Atun returns to the occupied areas from Ankara. 
Turkey is expected to clarify some points of the 21 March UN 
document, which, according to the Turkish side, has been 
modified. 
  U.S. officials said the Turkish explanations constitute no 
dramatic development or new proposals. Asked whether the Greek 
side will accept them, the same officials said they do not 
intend to suggest something that will not bear fruit. 
Discussing access to Famagusta, the U.S. officials said there 
will be no Turkish troops or armed Turkish Cypriots near the 
road linking the free areas with the fenced-off area. 
  A UN official denied reports that the procedure will be 
suspended for two months, stressing that a negative report will 
be issued if there is a negative Turkish reply. Referring to 
the adoption of alternative ways to implement the UN 
resolutions, a Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation correspondent 
reported that there is a shift in views at the UN Security 
Council, something that may delay a decision until 15 June, when 
UNFICYP's [UN Forces in Cyprus] mandate is expected to be 
renewed. 

</TEXT>

