<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Solana Welcomes EU Support for Bosnia Peace Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Solana Welcomes EU Support for Bosnia Peace Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605224094 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 2100 GMT 
16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605224094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Over to the Balkan crisis. The fighting 
continues around the Bosnian city of Tuzla that was attacked 
after the Muslim forces said that they had made territorial 
gains at the Serbs' expense. Meanwhile, diplomatic initiatives 
to end the war continue. The European Union [EU] foreign 
ministers have shown their support for the international plan 
agreed on last week, describing it as the only realistic way to 
end the conflict. From Brussels, here is our correspondent 
Nacho Hernandez. 
  [Hernandez] The EU supports the agreement reached at the 
Geneva meeting on Bosnia-Herzegovina despite its rejection by 
the parties in conflict. The Twelve see the fact that Russia, 
the United States, the United Nations, and the EU have a unified 
position in Bosnia-Herzegovina as a positive move. Spanish 
Foreign Minister Javier Solana said that for the first time 
positions are coordinated. 
  [Begin Solana recording] If we are able to make this so by 
focusing all of our energies on it over the next few days. I 
repeat that the agreement that was reached with all the 
concerned parties is something we have been wishing for a good 
many months. [end recording] 
  [Hernandez] Furthermore, the Twelve have decided to grant 
the 
city of Mostar aid worth 7,500 million pesetas. The EU starts 
to administer the city of Mostar on 1 June. 

</TEXT>

