<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Says Most Military Cuts To Affect West </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ruehe Says Most Military Cuts To Affect West </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605175294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1645 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1605175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Warnemuende (DDP/ADN) -- Despite the savings in 
the Bundeswehr budget, there will not be any reduction in troops 
in the states of former East Germany nor will any investment 
plans be dropped. This was stated by Defense Minister Volker 
Ruehe on the sidelines of a sitting of the Bundesrat defense 
committee in Warnemuende on Monday [16 May]. Contracts 
totalling almost a billion marks will be awarded to the 
construction industry this year for the seven large-scale 
Bundeswehr projects in eastern Germany, including establishing a 
marine technology academy in Parow near Stralsund and the 
planned move of the marine office to Warnemuende. 
  Ruehe also announced that troop numbers would be increased 
according to plans in the east, increasing from the present 
19,200 to 23,000 soldiers and almost 7,000 civilian employees. 
The figure of 20,000, by which the Bundeswehr is to be cut over 
the next few years, will mainly be saved in the states of the 
former West Germany, the defense minister said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

